Yes, you can use conditionals to choose different colors for layout elements based on the day and night themes. Here's an example of how you can achieve this:

1. Define the colors: Create separate color resources for day and night themes in your `res/values/colors.xml` and `res/values-night/colors.xml` files respectively. Give them the same name, but specify different color values. For example:

```xml
<!-- res/values/colors.xml -->
<color name="theme_color">#FFFFFF</color>

<!-- res/values-night/colors.xml -->
<color name="theme_color">#000000</color>
```

2. Apply the color in your layout XML: In your layout XML file, use the color resource by referencing it with `@color/theme_color` like this:

```xml
<TextView
    android:layout_width="wrap_content"
    android:layout_height="wrap_content"
    android:textColor="@color/theme_color"
    ...
/>
```

3. Select the appropriate color programmatically: In your activity's `onCreate()` method, you can check the device's current mode using `getResources().getConfiguration().uiMode & Configuration.UI_MODE_NIGHT_MASK` and then set the desired color based on the theme. For example:

```java
int themeColorResId;
if ((getResources().getConfiguration().uiMode & Configuration.UI_MODE_NIGHT_MASK) == Configuration.UI_MODE_NIGHT_YES) {
    // Night mode
    themeColorResId = R.color.theme_color_night;
} else {
    // Day mode
    themeColorResId = R.color.theme_color;
}

// Apply the color dynamically to your layout element
TextView textView = findViewById(R.id.your_text_view);
textView.setTextColor(ContextCompat.getColor(this, themeColorResId));
```

In this code snippet, the appropriate color resource will be selected based on the day or night theme, and then applied dynamically to your layout element.

Make sure to replace `R.id.your_text_view` with the actual ID of the layout element you wish to tint.

By using this approach, you can have different color values for day and night themes and apply them dynamically based on the selected theme.

To add a dark theme switch to your screen and handle the change when the button is tapped, you can follow these steps:

1. Add a ToggleButton: Replace the `ImageButton` in your layout XML with a `ToggleButton` element. Modify your code to include the necessary attributes. For example:

```xml
<ToggleButton
    android:id="@+id/darkModeToggle"
    android:layout_width="wrap_content"
    android:layout_height="wrap_content"
    android:layout_gravity="center"
    android:background="@color/white"
    android:importantForAccessibility="no"
    android:paddingVertical="12dp"
    android:paddingStart="8dp"
    android:paddingEnd="12dp"
    android:src="@drawable/off"
    tools:ignore="ImageContrastCheck" />
```

2. Implement the toggle functionality: In your activity class, access the `ToggleButton` and set an `OnCheckedChangeListener` to handle the toggle event. Inside the listener, check the state of the toggle and update the theme accordingly. Here's an example:

```java
ToggleButton darkModeToggle = findViewById(R.id.darkModeToggle);
darkModeToggle.setOnCheckedChangeListener(new CompoundButton.OnCheckedChangeListener() {
    @Override
    public void onCheckedChanged(CompoundButton buttonView, boolean isChecked) {
        if (isChecked) {
            // Dark theme enabled, apply dark theme
            AppCompatDelegate.setDefaultNightMode(AppCompatDelegate.MODE_NIGHT_YES);
        } else {
            // Dark theme disabled, apply light theme
            AppCompatDelegate.setDefaultNightMode(AppCompatDelegate.MODE_NIGHT_NO);
        }
        recreate(); // Recreate the activity to apply the theme changes
    }
});
```

3. Apply the theme change: In the `onCheckedChanged` method, based on the checked state of the toggle button, you can use `AppCompatDelegate.setDefaultNightMode()` to set the appropriate night mode. Call `recreate()` to recreate the activity and apply the new theme immediately.

Make sure you have the necessary dependencies in your project, such as the AppCompat support library (`androidx.appcompat:appcompat`) for using `AppCompatDelegate`.

By following these steps, you'll be able to add a dark theme switch to your screen and handle the theme change when the button is tapped.
